# <%= BasketContent.model_name.human %>

This feature provides a tool to calculate the content and value of <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %> for each delivery. It allows you to define which products go into each <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %> and configure how quantities are distributed across <%= BasketSize.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>.

## Products {#products}

Before configuring <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %>, you need to set up your [products](/basket_content_products). Each product has a name, a unit (kg or pieces), a unit price, and optionally a URL linking to the producer's website.

Products are reusable across deliveries — once created, they can be selected when adding content to any delivery. The price and quantities from the last use are automatically saved and pre-filled when adding the product to a new delivery.

## Configuring <%= BasketContent.model_name.human %> {#configuring-basket-contents}

From [the <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> page](/basket_contents), select a delivery to view and manage its contents. For each delivery, you can add products and configure how they are distributed across <%= BasketSize.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>.

### Distribution

For each product, you set the quantity per <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> for each <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %>. Percentage sliders let you adjust the split between sizes proportionally, and the total quantity updates automatically based on your per-size quantities and the current number of <%= Basket.model_name.human(count: 2).downcase %>.

Two preset buttons are available for quick distribution:

- **Pro rata by price**: splits quantities proportionally based on each <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %>'s price, so a size that costs twice as much gets roughly twice the quantity.
- **In equal parts**: gives the same quantity to every <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %>.

A live preview shows <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> counts and prices.

### Depots

Each <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> entry can be limited to specific depots. This is useful when there isn't enough of a product to supply all depots. When depot groups are configured, depots are visually grouped in the form with a group-level toggle to quickly select or deselect all depots within a group.

### Duplicating Contents

To save time, you can duplicate all <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> from one delivery to another using the sidebar action on the <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> page. This is particularly handy when your <%= Basket.model_name.human.downcase %> composition is similar from week to week.

### Prices {#prices}

When viewing a specific delivery, a prices panel appears above the product list for any products with a unit price set. For each <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %>, it shows the calculated content price alongside the difference from the base price.

When depots receive different basket prices — for example because some products are only assigned to certain depots — the panel displays a min–max price range. Hovering over each value reveals which depots correspond to it.

A collapsible section labeled with the fiscal year shows the cumulative year-to-date price difference for deliveries so far, broken down by delivery cycle when more than one is configured. Colored dots on the summary give a quick status at a glance: green means the cumulative value is above the planned total (>5%), red means below, and neutral means close to target (±5%).

## Displaying Contents to Members {#displaying-contents-to-members}

<%= BasketContent.model_name.human %> can optionally be displayed to your members on the deliveries page of their account. Each member sees only the products relevant to their specific <%= BasketSize.model_name.human.downcase %> and depot. This must be enabled from [your settings](/settings#basket_content).

### Visibility Window

To give you time to finalize the <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> before they become visible, you can configure a number of hours before midnight on the delivery day when the contents become visible. For example, with the default value of 12 hours, contents for a Thursday delivery will become visible on Wednesday at noon.

### Display Options

Several options are available to customize the display:

- **Title**: The heading shown above the product list (a default is provided).
- **Note**: An optional note displayed below the product list, for example to indicate that last-minute changes are possible (a default is provided, leave blank to hide).
- **Display quantity**: When enabled, the quantity is shown next to each product name, e.g. "Carrots (250g)".

The current visibility status for each delivery is shown in the sidebar of [the <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> page](/basket_contents) when viewing a specific coming delivery.

## Delivery Sheets {#delivery-sheets}

<%= BasketContent.model_name.human %> can also be included on printed delivery sheets (PDFs). When enabled from [the <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> settings](/settings#basket_content), each sheet will display the product list with quantities. See [the delivery sheets documentation](/handbook/deliveries#basket-content-sheets) for details.

## Newsletter Integration {#newsletter-integration}

<%= BasketContent.model_name.human %> are also available in newsletter templates using [Liquid syntax](https://shopify.github.io/liquid). The default ["Next delivery" newsletter template](/newsletter_templates) already includes a <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> section. If your template doesn't include it, or if you'd like to customize it, you can use the following code:

~~~ liquid
{% if basket.contents.size > 0 and basket.quantity > 0 %}
  <h2><%= BasketContent.model_name.human(count: 2) %></h2>

  <span>{{ basket.description }}:</span>
  <ul>
    {% for content in basket.contents %}
      <li>{{ content.product }} ({{ content.quantity }})</li>
    {% endfor %}
  </ul>
{% endif %}
~~~

Each <%= BasketContent.model_name.human.downcase %> in the loop provides the following attributes:

- `content.product`: The product name
- `content.quantity`: The formatted quantity (e.g. "250g", "3pc")
- `content.unit`: The raw unit ("kg" or "pc")
- `content.price`: The formatted price for this product (if a unit price is set)
- `content.unit_price`: The formatted unit price (if set)
- `content.product_url`: The product URL (if set)
